Bounded Monotonic Sequences

           Definitions

                       { }
           A sequence  a n   is bounded from above if there exists a number M such that  a ≤  M  for all n. The
                                                                                         n
                                                                                                 { }
                                           { }
           number M is an upper bound for  a  n   but no number less than M is an upper bound for  a n  , then M is the
                                 { }
           least upper bound for  a n  .


                       { }
           A sequence  a n   is bounded from below if there exists a number m such that  a ≥  m  for all n. The number
                                                                                        n
                                   { }
                                                                  { }
           m is an lower bound for  a n  . If m is a lower bound for  a n   but no number greater than m is a lower
                                                                 { }
                     { }
           bound for  a n  , then m is the greatest lower bound for  a n  .



















                                                         { }
             { }
           If  a n   is bounded from above and below, the  a n  is bounded.
             { }
                                        { }
           If  a n   is not bounded, then  a n   is an unbounded sequence.






























